CLASS SYSTEM
Possibly a Hero | Class Mechanics Specification
STATUS: Draft

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

1. FOUNDATIONAL CONTEXT

The class is the hero's shape for this run. Not their identity forever — their
identity right now. It's the answer to a question the game asks at the start
of every session: how do you want to arrive?

Four classes. Per-run selection. No permanent assignment, no locked commitment
carried between runs. The player picks a class before the map loads, and that
choice determines their movement type, their opening offensive capability, and
exactly how they look arriving to work. Then the run begins, and the class
starts earning a reputation of its own.

Class selection is one layer of a three-layer power architecture. The class
primary suite defines the foundation — the mechanical identity that is
entirely this class's and nobody else's. Hero powers and the support pool
build on top of that foundation during the run. They are shared across all
four classes. They are not the foundation. They are everything that gets added
to it. The layers are distinct. They stay distinct. No hero power encroaches
on what the class primary suite owns, and no support crosses that line either.

Mastery accumulated through successful runs is permanent. The class itself is
per-run. The record of what a player has done with a class — the unlocks
earned, the progression logged — does not reset between runs and does not
reset when the player picks a different class. A player can spend a week
running Speedster and return to Brawler with exactly as many Brawler unlocks
as they had before they left. The class waits. The record holds.

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
2. THE FOUR CLASSES
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

BRAWLER
Movement: Leaping
Intro: The Brawler leaps into frame and lands hard enough to crack the
pavement. Camera swings up to isometric. The first thing the city sees is the
impact. The second thing it sees is someone already standing in it.

Identity: Physical. Grounded. Space-controlling. The Brawler does not arrive
in the fight — the fight arrives around them. Every enemy that gets too
close is making a mistake. Every enemy that stands in the wrong place is one
Shockwave away from understanding that. The Brawler reads a battlefield
through position — who is where, what that cluster means, and whether the
ground is about to become a weapon. The fight is close. It is loud. It ends
when the Brawler decides it ends.

---

SPEEDSTER
Movement: Super Speed
Intro: The Speedster blurs in from off-screen. Camera snaps up with the
motion blur still resolving around them. They were somewhere else a moment ago.
They might be somewhere else again before the city finishes deciding how to
feel about the entrance.

Identity: Fast. Unpredictable. Momentum-driven. The Speedster's combat
philosophy is the same as their arrival philosophy: be somewhere, do something,
be somewhere else. An enemy tracking the Speedster's last position is tracking
history. A Speedster who commits to one angle is a Speedster making an
uncharacteristic mistake. The speed is the offense. The offense is the speed.
The blur is not a visual effect — it is a tactical statement.

---

BLASTER
Movement: Teleportation
Intro: The Blaster teleports in. Hard cut to isometric — no drift, no settle,
no transition. One frame they are not there. Next frame they are. The camera
does not ease into it. The Blaster does not ease into anything.

Identity: Precision at range. Space controlled through energy. The Blaster
does not need to be close to the problem. The problem is close to the Blaster
when the Blaster decides it is, and not before. They arrive without
announcement. They fire without wind-up. The Gravity Well does not ask the
enemy's permission before pulling everything into the same unfortunate
location. The Blaster is exact, and exact things tend to resolve exactly as
intended.

---

TACTICIAN
Movement: Vehicle
Intro: The Tactician rolls in on the vehicle. Camera lifts steadily and settles
with the deliberateness of someone who planned the approach before the run
started. This is not an entrance. This is an arrival on schedule.

Identity: Strategic. Infrastructure-minded. Prepared. The Tactician's vehicle
is not a power-up — it is the Tactician. There is no dismount. There is no
exit mechanic. The vehicle is permanent for the duration of the run because the
Tactician came with a plan and the plan includes the vehicle. Deployable
Turrets are not improvisation. The Rocket Launcher is not a surprise. The
Tactician already knew what was going to be needed. They brought it.

---

MOVEMENT IS CLASS-LOCKED.
Movement is not player-selectable. It is the class. A Brawler leaps. A
Speedster runs. A Blaster teleports. A Tactician drives. These are not items
in a menu. They are the mechanical expression of who the class is and how the
class exists in the city.

Flight is not in the movement pool. Wall crawling is not in the movement pool.
Both have been removed entirely. The Tactician's vehicle is permanent — there
is no exit mechanic, no dismount option, and no run state in which the
Tactician is not in the vehicle.

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
3. PRIMARY OFFENSIVE SUITES
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Each class has three offensive powers. Together they form the class primary
suite — the only mechanical layer that is class-specific. Everything else
the player builds during a run comes from the shared pools. These three powers
belong entirely to this class. No other class touches them.

The first power is available from run one. The second and third unlock through
class mastery — through the record of successful runs with that class, not
through any city building or construction choice. City buildings are mirrors.
They do not gate primary power access.

---

BRAWLER

Starter (available from run one):
SUPER STRENGTH
Single target. The Brawler hits one thing very hard. Everything else in the
immediate vicinity is aware of this. The fundamental Brawler statement: I am
here, you are near me, and now we are both dealing with that.

10 Successful Runs:
SHOCKWAVE / IMPACT BURST
Area of effect. The Brawler hits the ground instead of the enemy. The ground
has opinions about nearby enemies. Shockwave rewards the Brawler who has been
learning to read clusters — who sees six enemies standing together and
understands that as an opportunity, not a problem.

30 Successful Runs:
ELASTICITY / STRETCH
Mid-range combat. The Brawler's reach extends. Close-range identity stays
intact but the engagement envelope expands — enemies that thought they had
found a safe distance find out they measured incorrectly. The Brawler who
reaches 30 successful runs is not the same Brawler who started. Elasticity
reflects that.

---

SPEEDSTER

Starter (available from run one):
SPEED STRIKE
Single target. Rapid combo output. The Speedster hits the same enemy many
times before that enemy can develop a coherent response to being hit once.
High-frequency, momentum-native, everything the Speedster's movement type
is already communicating.

10 Successful Runs:
VELOCITY SLAM
Momentum-based impact. Skill-driven. The Speedster's speed becomes the weapon
rather than the delivery system for the weapon. Velocity Slam rewards
commitment — a Speedster who has been learning to build and spend momentum
rather than just accumulate it. The slam lands harder when the run-up was
longer. The player already knows this after ten runs. That is why it unlocks
at ten.

30 Successful Runs:
TORNADO
Area of effect. Environmental chaos. The Speedster stops hitting the enemy
and starts hitting the space the enemy is standing in. Thirty runs of momentum-
reading creates a player who understands what it means to own a zone —
to spin something into existence in the center of a cluster and let the world
disagree with everything inside it.

---

BLASTER

Starter (available from run one):
ENERGY BLAST
Single target. Precision output at range. The Blaster points. Something
happens to the thing being pointed at. Energy Blast is the clearest possible
expression of Blaster identity: the gap between the hero and the target is
not a problem, it is the entire point.

10 Successful Runs:
ELEMENTAL SURGE
Per-run element selection: fire, ice, or lightning. Each carries distinct
status effects. This is directed elemental projection — force lightning aimed
at a target, concentrated fire fired from the hero's body, precision ice
released and controlled. It comes from the hero. It travels toward something
specific. It does not fill a room. It does not call weather. It arrives
exactly where it was aimed, with the element the Blaster chose before the
run started.

Note on Elemental Surge and Tempest: these powers share a lightning element
and are not the same power. Elemental Surge is directed and precise — the
Blaster projects it. Tempest is environmental — the storm answers the hero
rather than coming from them. A Blaster running both in the same run is a
precision energy projector who can also call storms. They are not doubling up.
They are operating on two separate planes simultaneously.

30 Successful Runs:
GRAVITY WELL
Area of effect. Tactical. The Blaster deploys a gravitational anomaly that
pulls everything in range toward a point of their choosing, then detonates.
Gravity Well is the power of a Blaster who has learned to think in clusters —
who sees a scattered enemy formation and understands how to make it stop being
scattered. Thirty runs of precision output earns the right to rearrange the
battlefield before addressing it.

---

TACTICIAN

Starter (available from run one):
RIFLE
Single target. Precision at distance. The Tactician shoots a thing they have
already identified as worth shooting. Clean, intentional, no ambiguity about
where the damage goes. The Rifle is the Tactician's position statement: I
know what I'm doing, I know what I'm targeting, and I have already thought
about whether this is the right call.

10 Successful Runs:
DEPLOYABLE TURRETS
Utility and area control. The Tactician establishes coverage. The Turrets
handle the zone while the Tactician handles the plan. This is the Tactician
operating at something closer to their natural state — deploying infrastructure,
creating controlled space, and letting the prepared environment do the work a
less-prepared hero would have to do themselves.

30 Successful Runs:
ROCKET LAUNCHER
Area of effect. Destruction. The Tactician brought ordinance because they knew
the target would require it. Thirty runs of strategic layering earns the power
that removes entire sections of an encounter from consideration. The Rocket
Launcher is not imprecision — it is scale. The Tactician who reaches thirty
runs knows exactly when to stop being surgical and start being structural.

