4. CLASS MASTERY AND UNLOCK STRUCTURE
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Every class starts with one offensive power available.

Second offensive power unlocks at 10 successful runs with that class.
Third offensive power unlocks at 30 successful runs with that class.

Unlocks are cumulative and permanent. They do not reset between runs. They
do not reset when the player switches to a different class. They do not
regress on failed runs. A failed run does not count toward unlock progress and
does not subtract from it. The record holds.

Unlock thresholds are per-class. Ten Brawler runs do not contribute to
Speedster mastery. Each class's record belongs to that class.

The unlock thresholds are not arbitrary numbers. Ten successful runs with a
class is enough to understand the starter power well enough to layer something
new on top of it. Thirty successful runs is enough to have genuinely developed
a playstyle — to have arrived at the point where the third power expands a
real identity rather than a theoretical one. The progression gate is designed
around what the player has actually learned by the time the unlock fires.

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
5. THE THREE POWER LAYERS
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Three distinct layers build the hero's capability during a run. They are
designed to stay distinct. The separation is structural and intentional —
each layer does something the other two do not, and none of them trespasses
into what the others own.

At each milestone (level up), the player chooses one option from three
genuinely viable candidates:
- A class primary upgrade — deepens class identity
- A hero power — adds a new tool, broadens capability
- A support option — modifies existing powers, shifts build interactions

No option is the obvious correct answer. The run's character emerges from
the weight of all these decisions across all its milestones — not from a
preset loadout the player carried in.

---

LAYER 1 — CLASS PRIMARY
Class-specific. Unlocks through mastery. Defines class identity. Selected at
run start when more than one is available. The class primary suite is the
only layer the class owns exclusively. It is the foundation everything else
gets built on. Hero powers and supports broaden and modify the foundation —
they do not become the foundation.

---

LAYER 2 — HERO POWERS
Shared pool across all classes. Fully random mid-run pickups offered at
milestone moments. Offensive with utility upside. The entire pool is available
from run one — no city building controls which powers can appear. Every power
in the pool has standalone offensive value before combo value. The ridiculous
combination the player didn't plan for is not a malfunction. It is the point.

Full pool (eleven powers):

MAGNETISM
Pull enemies together. Redirect projectiles back at their sources. Strip
weapons. The Brawler who combines Magnetism with Shockwave is doing
something the Brawler class was designed to make possible: pulling a cluster
and landing an AOE in the center of it. Every other class benefits differently.
The power works regardless.

FREEZE FRAME
Brief local time dilation. Everything in range stops. The player doesn't.
The window it opens is the player's to use however they've built.

TEMPEST
Lightning strikes from above. Wind gusts. Localized storms. The weather
answers the hero — it is not coming from the hero. Thor's lightning bolt
called down, not force lightning fired out. Environmental, atmospheric, spatial.
This is the storm. The hero is the reason it's here.

TREMOR
Fissures open. The ground shakes. Terrain becomes a weapon — edges, cracks,
obstacles, and elevation shifts that enemies and the hero both have to navigate,
except the hero caused them and can plan around them.

RIFT
Displaces enemies around the map. Intentionally chaotic. The player who picks
Rift is choosing to introduce disorder into a fight on the theory that they
can exploit it faster than the enemies can recover from it. Sometimes this is
correct. The hero power pool allows for theories to be tested.

TOXIN
Damage over time. Spreads between enemies in contact. A patient power for a
player who understands that not everything has to resolve immediately. The
spread mechanic rewards positioning — putting the first target somewhere the
spread has somewhere to go.

SONIC SCREAM
Stuns. Disorients. Chain damages through a cluster. The Sonic Scream does
not pick one target — it addresses the room.

SUMMON
One pool entry. Class-adaptive expression. The player picks up Summon and
gets the version native to their class: Gorilla (Brawler — animal companion,
a second thing in the fight the enemy has to account for), Double Time
(Speedster — speed clone, another version of the problem running at full
speed in a direction the enemy didn't anticipate), Specter (Blaster —
spectral ally, phases through walls, attacks from positions without
conventional access), Sentinel (Tactician — combat drone, autonomous,
tactical, already deployed before the enemy arrived). One slot in the pool.
Four expressions.

Summon is a hero power. It appears in the shared random pool. It is
class-adaptive in expression and native to class identity — but it is not
a class primary power. The distinction matters. The summon is something the
run adds on top of the foundation, not something the class came in with.

---

LAYER 3 — SUPPORT POOL
Shared across all classes. Class-agnostic. Accumulates during the run.
Every support has standalone value regardless of what primary power or hero
power combination it joins. No support encroaches on class identity.

Full pool (8 supports):
Combat: Reflexes, Power Surge, Blast Radius, Precision Strike, Rapid Recovery
Utility: Overdrive, Fast Track
Safety: Last Stand

The support pool uses names the genre already knows. A player who has run
a roguelite before understands what Blast Radius does before the tooltip
finishes loading. That legibility is intentional. The support layer should not
require explanation — it should invite experimentation.

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
6. THE MENTOR SYSTEM
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Each class has a mentor. Each mentor has a building. Each building has been
in the city this whole time.

The four class-specific buildings exist from early progression. They look like
nothing. They are not nothing. When the mentor relationship unlocks through
class progression and playtime, the building reveals what it actually is —
and the player realizes they have walked past it a dozen times without
recognizing it. The reveal is the point. Hidden in plain sight is not a mystery
mechanic — it is a design statement about how the city works and what it has
been holding for the player without announcing it.

Each mentor introduction is a three-panel comic book moment. Not a cutscene.
Not a tutorial. A moment with the compositional weight and kinetic energy of
a comic book splash page that happens to be interactive.

Mentor introductions are world events. They generate content across all three
feedback channels — Citizens, Superhero Community, and Rex Flynn on Exposed —
because the world noticed. The hero gaining a mentor is not a private
transaction. The city has opinions about it before the hero has had time to
process the meeting.

Mechanically: mentors provide narrative context for why advanced class powers
exist and why they are teachable. The unlock itself remains tied to run
completion — 10 successful runs for the second power, 30 for the third.
The mentor is the story of why the unlock happens. The mentor is not the gate
that controls it. City buildings are mirrors. Mentor buildings follow the same
rule.

---

BRAWLER MENTOR — Like recognizes like.

The mentor sees the player fight from across the street. Nobody told them to
look. Nothing flagged the encounter as significant. They were just nearby,
they recognized what they were seeing, and they walked over.

No mysticism. No technology. No dramatic framing. A veteran fighter identifying
good form — or bad form — and having something to say about it. Direct.
Physical. Slightly gruff. The introduction is already the first lesson. The
mentor has an opinion about the Brawler's technique before a word of welcome
has been exchanged. The handshake, if there is one, comes after the correction.

The building that was non-descript yesterday has a sign today. Maybe it
always had a sign. The Brawler just wasn't looking at it the right way.

---

SPEEDSTER MENTOR — Sense the presence of another.

The player turns around. The mentor is already there.

The player did not hear them arrive. They do not know how long the mentor has
been standing there. The mentor is not performing a dramatic entrance — they
simply appeared because they sensed something and went toward it. Attuned in
ways that are not entirely explainable. Comfortable with the fact that this is
not explainable. The Speedster who has been running for weeks might recognize
the feeling of being near someone else with the same kind of speed. Might not.
Either way, the mentor was already standing there when the question formed.

The building does not announce itself. It never did. The Speedster has been
fast enough to notice it and not noticed it. The mentor noticed the Speedster
first.

---

BLASTER MENTOR — The city reacts.

Lights flicker. Die in sequence across two city blocks — not all at once, in
sequence, as if something is moving through the infrastructure with a specific
direction. Electronics glitch. Phones reboot mid-call. The intersection ahead
goes dark.

The player investigates. What they find is not an enemy.

It is a person who has been living with uncontrolled energy output for years.
Managing it. Minimizing it. Mostly succeeding. They recognized the player's
energy signature from six blocks away — a precision that implies they have
spent a long time learning to read exactly this kind of output. The blackout
was not an accident. It was a greeting. The kind of greeting that felt
proportionate to someone who has lived for years in a city that mostly flinches
at what they do, and wanted to signal before they startled.

The building was dark when it needed to be. Now there's light in the windows.

---

TACTICIAN MENTOR — Tech detects tech.

The player's equipment flags a danger alert. Unknown technology nearby —
signature that does not match any catalogued threat profile, but is
sophisticated enough to register as one. The player investigates, approaching
the source with the assessment already written: possible enemy, advanced kit,
unknown capabilities.

They find a person. Someone whose equipment makes the player's look like a
prototype, and who was fully aware the player's alert was going to fire, and
who set it up that way deliberately. Adversarial before collaborative. A test
without a briefing. The mentor wanted to see how the player approached a
technical unknown before deciding whether the meeting was worth having.

It was worth having. The mentor had already decided that before the player
arrived. The alert was the invitation.

The building that looked like maintenance infrastructure turns out to be
nothing like maintenance infrastructure. It has been operational this whole
time. The player just didn't have clearance to see it.

